---

## 🎯 Overview

This enhancement adds a comprehensive record management system with relationship linking capabilities. Each category can now contain detailed records with custom fields, and records can be linked together with typed relationships.

### What's New

- **Records**: Detailed entries within categories with custom fields
- **Relations**: Bidirectional links between records with type definitions
- **Custom Fields**: Dynamic attributes (text, number, date, URL, email, phone, boolean)
- **Form Lock**: Prevent accidental additions after record creation
- **Rich Detail View**: Tabbed interface with overview, relations, and activity
- **Search & Filter**: Find records by title, description, or custom field values
- **View Modes**: Grid and list layouts

---

## ✨ Features

### Record Management

- ✅ Create records with title, description, and status
- ✅ Add unlimited custom fields per record
- ✅ Support for 7 field types: text, number, date, URL, email, phone, boolean
- ✅ Draft, Published, and Archived status workflow
- ✅ Real-time synchronization
- ✅ Offline support with IndexedDB persistence

### Relationship System

- ✅ Link any record to any other record
- ✅ Predefined relation types (manufactured_by, stored_in, depends_on, etc.)
- ✅ Custom relation types
- ✅ Bidirectional linking
- ✅ Relation descriptions
- ✅ Visual relation display with navigation

### User Experience

- ✅ Form lock mechanism after creation
- ✅ Modal detail view with tabs
- ✅ Search and filter records
- ✅ Grid and list view modes
- ✅ Responsive design
- ✅ Dark mode support
- ✅ Toast notifications

---

## 🏗️ Architecture

```
┌─────────────────┐
│     Users       │
└────────┬────────┘
         │ 1:N
         ▼
┌─────────────────┐
│    Systems      │
└────────┬────────┘
         │ 1:N
         ▼
┌─────────────────┐
│   Categories    │◄────┐
└────────┬────────┘     │ Self-referencing
         │ 1:N          │ (parent/child)
         ▼              │
┌─────────────────┐     │
│    Records      │     │
└────────┬────────┘     │
         │ 1:N          │
         ▼              │
┌─────────────────┐     │
│ Custom Fields   │     │
└─────────────────┘     │
         │              │
         ▼              │
┌─────────────────┐     │
│   Relations     │─────┘
│  (Many-to-Many) │
└─────────────────┘
```

### Data Flow

```
User Authentication
    ↓
Load System & Category
    ↓
Setup Realtime Listeners (Records & Relations)
    ↓
Render Records Grid
    ↓
User Interactions:
    • Create Record → Add Custom Fields → Save
    • View Record → Open Detail Modal → Navigate Tabs
    • Add Relation → Search Records → Link with Type
    • Edit/Delete → Update Firestore → Re-render
```

---

## 📦 Installation

### Step 1: Add New Files

Create these new files in your project:

1. **records.html** - Record management interface
2. **records.js** - Record management logic
3. **firestore.rules** - Updated security rules
4. **firestore.indexes.json** - Database indexes

### Step 2: Update Existing Files

#### dashboard.html

Add the "View Records" button to the category template:

```html
<!-- In categoryItemTemplate, add before deleteBtn -->
<button class="viewRecords text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded bg-purple-600 text-white hover:bg-purple-700 transition" title="View Records">📄</button>
```

#### dashboard.js

Add the button handler in the `renderNode` function:

```javascript
// After archiveNodeBtn setup
const viewRecordsBtn = el.querySelector('.viewRecords');
viewRecordsBtn?.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  e.stopPropagation();
  window.location.href = `records.html?systemId=${currentSystemId}&categoryId=${node.id}`;
});
```

### Step 3: Deploy Firestore Rules

1. Go to Firebase Console
2. Navigate to Firestore Database → Rules
3. Copy and paste the security rules
4. Click "Publish"

### Step 4: Create Indexes

Option A - Automatic (when you run queries):
- Firestore will show index creation links in the console
- Click the links to auto-create required indexes

Option B - Manual:
1. Go to Firestore Database → Indexes
2. Create composite indexes as specified in firestore.indexes.json

Option C - Firebase CLI:
```bash
firebase deploy --only firestore:indexes
```

